Answers from HW 1, Part 1:
Each variable (or column) represents details about each penguin, whether its species type, island, year (most likely the year when the penguin was born), sex, and morphology–specifically a penguin’s bill length and depth, its flipper length, and its body mass (by grams). “Species” and “island” are considered as nominal categorical values because they are not numbers (hence “categorical”), but the variable value doesn’t have a ranking (“nominal”). On the other hand, the morphological attributes I listed above are considered as numerical variables. But, “year” variable is specifically a discrete numerical variable because you can count it (it’s arguably not measurable because it doesn’t change when it’s set… I guess), while the others are continuous numerical variables because continuous values need to be measured (so there could be decimals).

  1. Make a scatterplot of the bill length (y-axis) vs. the bill depth (x-axis).

Correct. I did something extra where I put an r^2 line (not necessary), but I wanted it because I needed to be able to see if there was even a a linear relationship between bill length and depth

Answers from HW 1, Part 1:

library(ggplot2) #make graphs
library(ggridges) #MOARE fun graph options

#Scatter plot
ggplot(data = penguins,
       aes(x = bill_depth_mm, y = bill_length_mm)) +
  
  geom_point(color = "#008080",
             alpha = 0.6,
             show.legend = FALSE) +
  
  labs(x = "Bill Depth (in mm)", 
       y = "Bill Length (in mm)",
       title = "Penguin Bill Depth vs. Bill Length") +
  
#Adding r^2 function to better observe linear relationship
  geom_smooth(method = "lm",
              color = "black",
              se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

    Correct. Same answer as solutions, just with r^2 line.

Answers from HW 1, Part 1: Based off of the r^2 line drawn, it seems that the linear relationship between bill depth and length is rather weak, and somewhat negative.

Answers from HW 1, Part 1:

#Make a density plot comparing flipper lengths to species AND sex
ggplot(data = penguins,
       aes(x = flipper_length_mm)) +
  
  geom_density(
    alpha = 0.5,
   show.legend = FALSE) +
  
  facet_grid(rows = vars(species),
             cols = vars(sex),
             scales = "free_y") +
  
  labs(x = "Flipper Length (in mm)",
       title = "Flipper length distribution to Species and Sex")

#Box plot comparing flipper lengths to sex
ggplot(data = penguins,
       aes(x = flipper_length_mm,
           y = sex)) +

  labs(x = "Flipper Length (in mm)",
       y = "Biological Sex",
       title = "Flipper length distribution to Sex") +

Answers from HW 1, Part 1:

#Bargraphs w/ year

#Sex Distribution per Year
ggplot(data = penguins,
       aes(x = year,
           fill = sex)) +
  
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  
  labs(x = "Year",
       y = "Percent(%) Penguins",
       title = "Sex Distribution per Year")

#Species Distribution per Year
ggplot(data = penguins,
       aes(x = year,
           fill = species)) +
  
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  
  labs(x = "Year",
       y = "Percent(%) Penguins",
       title = "Species Distribution per Year")

#Island Distribution per Year
ggplot(data = penguins,
       aes(x = year,
           fill = island)) +
  
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  
  labs(x = "Year",
       y = "Percent(%) Penguins",
       title = "Island Distribution per Year")

#Combined data
ggplot(data = penguins,
       aes(x = year)) +
  
  geom_bar() +
  
  facet_grid(rows = vars(island),
             cols = vars(species)) +
  
  labs(x = "Year",
       title = "Island and Species Distribution per Year")

First off, the graph that displayed this information best is the last graph, due to its facet rendering. Now, if we recalled earlier, both Chinstrap and Gentoo species live in their respective islands only (Dream and Biscoe), while the Adelie species live on all three islands. Based off of the last graph, the data collected shows that all islands were targeted over time. So, this is a longitudinal study of all three islands and how each penguin species change (whether by population/island, sex/island, size, etc) over time.
